Contacting the API

We will define a few functions to help us contact the Pok√©mon API. In terms of endpoints, this API has many groups of them. Below are the groups with their respective endpoints:

  • Berries - Berries, Berry Firmnesses, and Berry Flavors.
  • Contests - Contest Types, Contest Effects, and Super Contest Effects
  • Encounters - Encounter Methods, Encounter Conditions, and Encounter Condition Values.
  • Evolutiobn - Evolution Chains Evolution Triggers
  • Games - Generations, Pokedexes, Version, and Version Groups.
  • Items - Item, Item Attributes, Item Categories, Item Fling Effects, and Item Pockets
  • Locations - Locations, Location Areas, Pal Park Areas, and Regions.
  • Machines - Machines
  • Moves - Moves, Move Ailments, Move Battle Styles, Move Categories, Move Damage Classes, Move Learn Methods, and Move Targets
  • Pok√©mon - Abilities, Characteristics, Egg Groups, Genders, Growth Rates, Natures, Pokeathlon Stats, Pok√©mon, Pokemon Location Areas, Pokemon Colors, Pokemon Forms, Pokemon Habitats, Pokemon Shapes, Stats, and Types
  • Utility - Languages and Common Models

In my eyes, the Pok√©mon and Moves groups seem to have some interesting endpoints we should explore.

pokemonMoves

Here we will define a function to grab all of the moves of any singular Pok√©mon. The function input can either be the id (integer or string) or name of the Pok√©mon (string), and the output will be a tibble of that Pok√©mon‚Äôs possible moves with their respective names, type, power, accuracy, and power points. Thus, this function effectively queries six endpoints, although only based on which Pok√©mon is chosen.

pokemonMoves <- function(pokemon, stats="all") {
  ###
  # This function returns a tibble of a given Pok√©mon's moves 
  # and their names, type, power, accuracy and power points. 
  ###
  
  #Even if ID or Name is given, the process for getting the data is the same
  data  <- fromJSON(paste0('https://pokeapi.co/api/v2/pokemon/',tolower(pokemon)))
  moves <- data$moves$move
  n     <- length(moves[,1])
  
  #Initialize output data.frame with a dummy row we will overwrite
  output <- data.frame(Name = "chr", 
                       Type = "chr",
                       Power = 0,
                       Accuracy = 0,
                       PP = 0)
  
  #Loop through each move and grab desired variables for each move
  for (i in 1:n) {
    move    <- fromJSON(moves$url[i])
    #Initialize new row with dumm
    new     <- data.frame(Name = "chr", 
                          Type = "chr",
                          Power = 0,
                          Accuracy = 0,
                          PP = 0)
    new[,1]  <- move$name
    new[,2]  <- move$type$name
    #Moves without a power will be given a power of 0 for the sake of this 
    #analysis.
    if (length(move$power) == 0) {
      new[,3] <- 0
    } else {
      new[,3] <- move$power
    }
    #Moves with infinite accuracy will be given an accuracy score of 100 
    #for the sake of this analysis.
    if (length(move$accuracy) == 0) {
      new[,4]   <- 100
    } else {
      new[,4]   <- move$accuracy
    }
    new[,5]     <- move$pp
    output[i,] <- new
  }
  
  #Now let's take into account the desired options
  if (stats == "all") {
    output <- as_tibble(output)
  } 
  
  return(output)
}

squirtleData <- pokemonMoves("squirtle")

It looks like most of Squirtle‚Äôs moves are either Normal or Water Type. That makes sense, considering Squirtle is a Water Type Pok√©mon!

It would be nice to take a look at the different powers of moves within each type. However, there are many different possibilities for the power of a move. Let‚Äôs define some categories for the different strengths of moves:

  • Status: Power is 0 - these moves have some alternate effect.
  • Weak: 0 \(<\) Power \(\leq\) 50
  • Decent: 50 \(<\) Power \(\leq\) 80
  • Strong: Power \(>\) 80

Let‚Äôs add a variable called Strength that categorizes the Power variable into these groups.

squirtleData$Strength <- 
  ifelse(squirtleData$Power == 0,"Status",
         ifelse(squirtleData$Power <= 50, "Weak",
                ifelse(squirtleData$Power <= 80, "Decent","Strong")))
squirtleData$Strength <- as.factor(squirtleData$Strength)
squirtleData$Strength <- ordered(squirtleData$Strength,
                                 levels = c("Status",
                                            "Weak",
                                            "Decent", 
                                            "Strong"))

With this new variable, let‚Äôs look at the distributions of different types of Squirtle‚Äôs moves within these categories.

kable(table(squirtleData$Strength,squirtleData$Type), "simple")
dark dragon fighting ghost ground ice normal poison psychic rock steel water
Status 1 0 2 1 1 3 23 1 3 0 2 4
Weak 0 0 2 0 1 0 7 0 1 1 0 4
Decent 1 0 3 0 1 2 7 0 1 2 0 8
Strong 0 2 2 0 0 2 5 0 0 0 1 5

Again, let‚Äôs take a visual look at distributions, with the color representing Strength this time.

plot2 <- ggplot(squirtleData, aes(x=Type, fill=Strength)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(title = "Types of Squirtle's Moves", y = "Count") 
plot2

It looks like a major reason Squirtle has so many Normal Type moves is because so many Status moves seem to be Normal Type.

Since we discuss the Power variable heavily from this point on, let‚Äôs remove moves from the Status category for the remainder of our analysis, as these moves all have a Power of zero.

squirtleData <- squirtleData %>%
  filter(squirtleData$Strength != "Status")

With this done, let‚Äôs look at a few numerical summaries of the Power variable within the remaining Strength categories.

table1 <- squirtleData %>%
  group_by(Strength) %>%
  summarise(Mean = round(mean(Power)), 
            Median = round(median(Power)),
            SD = round(sd(Power)))
kable(table1, "simple")

Weak 39 40 9

Now that we have an idea about the power of Squirtle‚Äôs moves, let‚Äôs incorporate the accuracy of Squirtle‚Äôs moves into this discussion. First, let‚Äôs plot the Power of Squirtle‚Äôs moves versus their Accuracy.

plot3 <- ggplot(squirtleData, aes(x=Accuracy, y=Power, color=Type, label=Name)) + 
  geom_point(position="jitter") + 
  labs(title = "Power vs Accuracy of Squirtle's Moves") + 
  scale_color_manual(values = manual)
plot3

However, this is not the whole story. In Pok√©mon, there is a mechanic called Same Type Attack Bonus, or STAB for short. This increases the effective power of moves that match a Pok√©mon‚Äôs type by 50%. So, Squirtle‚Äôs Water Type moves technically should deal 50% more damage. Let‚Äôs define a new variable to represent the Effective Power of Squirtle‚Äôs moves.

squirtleData$effPower <- 
  ifelse(squirtleData$Type == "water",
         squirtleData$Power*1.5,
         squirtleData$Power)

With this in mind, let us re-examine this plot of Power versus Accuracy of Squirtle‚Äôs moves by using this new variable.

plot4 <- ggplot(squirtleData, aes(x=Accuracy, y=effPower, color=Type, label=Name)) + 
  geom_point(position="jitter") +
  labs(title = "Effective Power vs Accuracy of Squirtle's Moves", y = "Effective Power") +
  scale_color_manual(values = manual)
plot4

Now we can see some definite outlying Water Type moves by taking into account Squirtle‚Äôs STAB.

We can create another categorical variable called Risk that splits up Accuracy into the following groups:

  • No Risk: Accuracy is 100
  • Low Risk: 80 \(\leq\) Accuracy \(<\) 100
  • High Risk: Accuracy \(<\) 80
squirtleData$Risk <- 
  ifelse(squirtleData$Accuracy == 100,"No Risk",
         ifelse(squirtleData$Accuracy >= 80, "Low Risk","High Risk"))
squirtleData$Risk <- as.factor(squirtleData$Risk)
squirtleData$Risk <- ordered(squirtleData$Risk,
                                 levels = c("No Risk",
                                            "Low Risk",
                                            "High Risk"))

Let‚Äôs look at the distribution of the different Strengths of moves within these Risk categories.

plot5 <- ggplot(squirtleData, aes(x=Risk, fill=Strength)) + 
  geom_bar() + 
  labs(title = "Risks of Squirtle's Moves", y = "Count") 
plot5

This distribution of the Strength levels within the different Risk categories makes a fair bit of sense. The risky moves are generally strong, while the weak and decent moves are generally less risky. Let‚Äôs look at some numerical summaries of Power within these Risk categories.

table2<- squirtleData %>%
  group_by(Risk) %>%
  summarise(Mean = round(mean(Power)), 
            Median = round(median(Power)),
            SD = round(sd(Power)))
kable(table2,"simple")
Risk Mean Median SD
No Risk 70 68 30
Low Risk 73 80 24
High Risk 108 105 10

Now we can clearly see the High Risk moves have a much higher average Power.

Let‚Äôs quantify this a little bit and see if we can find Squirtle‚Äôs best move while taking into account both Power and Accuracy. If Squirtle were to use a move with an Accuracy of 90%, then 10% of the time the move will miss and therefore have an Effective Power of zero in that case. So, the True Power of a move would be the overall average of it‚Äôs possible Effective Power values. Let‚Äôs define a variable to represent this.

\[\text{True Power} = \text{Effective Power} \times \frac{\text{Accuracy}}{100} \]

squirtleData$truePower <- squirtleData$effPower*squirtleData$Accuracy/100

With this variable defined, let‚Äôs try to find Squirtle‚Äôs top ten moves, ranked by their True Power.

squirtleData <- squirtleData %>%
  arrange(desc(truePower)) %>%
  select(Name, Type, Power, Accuracy, truePower)

kable(head(squirtleData, n=10), "simple",
      col.names = c("Name", "Type", "Power", "Accuracy", "True Power"))
Name Type Power Accuracy True Power
water-spout water 150 100 225.0
focus-punch fighting 150 100 150.0
surf water 90 100 135.0
hydro-pump water 110 80 132.0
skull-bash normal 130 100 130.0
aqua-tail water 90 90 121.5
double-edge normal 120 100 120.0
waterfall water 80 100 120.0
outrage dragon 120 100 120.0
dive water 80 100 120.0

From this table it seems Water Spout is Squirtle‚Äôs strongest move with a True Power of 225!

Conclusion

Of course, there are many factors not being taken into account in this analysis. For example, Water Spout becomes a weaker move if Squirtle is at lower HP. Additionally, we did not take into account the defending Pok√©mon‚Äôs typing, which could affect the damage output. We did not take into account the differences between the Physical and Special categories of moves within Pok√©mon, and how that might affect damage output. We did not take into account additional effects of Squirtle‚Äôs moves, which would add a layer of subjectivity to this analysis. There are many ways to make our analysis more thorough, but I think this was a fun start!
